# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "2.     The journal entry is as follows:"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "3.     The entry in the ledger is the rewriting of the journal entry in a place in the company’s records specific to the accounts concerned.  The two accounts affected being land and cash means that the manager needs to find the relevant 2 pages (in a paper based system) or computer files (in a computerized system) that track the company’s land and cash balances.  These ledgers are then updated to show that Land has increased by \\$10,000 and Cash has decreased by \\$10,000.  The same debit and credit notation is used in the ledgers as is used in the general journal –i.e. the increase in land is written in the left-hand column (debito) and the decrease in cash is written on the right (credito)."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "4.     The preparation of an unadjusted trial balance takes the raw material of all of the ledger balances and summarizes them on a single sheet of paper.  The debit and credit notation is used.  If an account has a debit balance, then it is written on the left side of the unadjusted trial balance (debito), and if it has a credit balance it is written on the right side (credito).  In the case of our purchase of the land for \\$10,000, the effect would be that the land account has increased by \\$10,000 and the cash account has decreased by \\$10,000.  This would be reflected in the unadjusted trial balance."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "5.     Adjusting the accounts is an important part of the accounting cycle.  Or example if, instead of buying land, we had bought an asset which has a limited life-span such as a patent which expires in 5 years, we would need to adjust the value of the patent asset on the balance sheet, decreasing it by one-fifth every year[1].  However, land has an indefinite life (even if the current buildings on the land are demolished, the underlying land can be used again and again by having new buildings constructed on it).  Therefore, in this simple case, no adjusting entry requires to be made, as the asset remains on the balance sheet at \\$10,000.  In either case, the managers must keep some documents or notes that state how they determined the life span of the asset (in the case of the patent) or that the asset has an indefinite life (in the case of land).  These notes or documents may be required by the auditors."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "6.     The effect of our transaction on the financial statements is confined to the balance sheet.  Similar to part 4, the effect would be that the land asset has increased by \\$10,000 and the cash asset has decreased by \\$10,000.  The balance sheet format, however, is not always based on the debit credit format.  Some balance sheets show the assets on the left (debit side) and the liabilities and stockholder’s equity on the right (credit side).  However, more complex companies customarily write the assets first, then show the liabilities and stockholder’s equity below them or on the next page.  If we had instead purchased a patent for \\$10,000, and that patent asset had decreased by \\$2,000 (5 year life), this would affect the income statement also – there would be an amortization expense of \\$2,000"
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/accounting-procedures-recording-transactions-financial/accounting-cycle-recording-transactions/a/the-seven-stages-of-the-basic-accounting-cycle</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "7.     When we talk about closing the accounts, we mean that the company’s balance sheet is updated and the company’s income statement is “zeroed out”.  The reason for this is that, at the end of each year, the company’s income statement has to be a “blank sheet”, because an income statement only covers what happed to the company in any one year, it cannot include the last year’s transactions as well.  The company’s balance sheet is not zeroed out, since the company’s assets and debts in place still exist and persist in the next year.  In the case of our simple transaction of purchasing land for \\$10,000, the effect of the transaction is confined to the balance sheet, so there is no need to zero out either the Land account or the cash account.  If we think of the other example of the purchase of a patent, because this would have been an expense of \\$2,000, this would affect the closing process.   Because amortization expense is shown on the income statement, this has to be zeroed out.  Expenses decrease the stockholder’s claim, so the effect of closing the amortization expense to zero is to decrease equity by \\$2000 [2]."
msgstr ""

