msgid "7.     When we talk about closing the accounts, we mean that the company’s balance sheet is updated and the company’s income statement is “zeroed out”.  The reason for this is that, at the end of each year, the company’s income statement has to be a “blank sheet”, because an income statement only covers what happed to the company in any one year, it cannot include the last year’s transactions as well.  The company’s balance sheet is not zeroed out, since the company’s assets and debts in place still exist and persist in the next year.  In the case of our simple transaction of purchasing land for $10,000, the effect of the transaction is confined to the balance sheet, so there is no need to zero out either the Land account or the cash account.  If we think of the other example of the purchase of a patent, because this would have been an expense of $2,000, this would affect the closing process.   Because amortization expense is shown on the income statement, this has to be zeroed out.  Expenses decrease the stockholder’s claim, so the effect of closing the amortization expense to zero is to decrease equity by $2000 [2]."
