msgid "Once the transaction analysis is complete the transaction must be translated into the debit and credit format and written in the general journal of the company’s accounts.  The debit and credit format helps keep track of increases in assets and claims, and assists in ensuring that a company’s accounts are in balance.  An increase in an asset, or a decrease in what is owed by the company, is a debit and is written on the left hand side of an accounting worksheet .   A decrease in an asset, or an increase in money owed by the company to others, is a credit and is written with an indent or tab, to show that it belongs on the right.  This is in accordance with the basic idea of bookkeeping that debit (latin: debere or Dr) is something owned by or owed to the company – a resource the company gets - and that a credit (latin: credere or Cr) is something owed by the company – the promise the company gives to pay back later (another meaning of credere is associated with belief, in this case belief that the company will pay back).  In his original accounting textbook, the originator of modern accounting, Pacioli, prefaced every debit with “To:” and every credit with “By:”.  “To” indicates the destination of the resource in the company.  “By:” indicates the claim or promise that is the source of the asset gained.  It’s important to note that debit and credit are used here in a different sense to that in regular conversation.  For example, we are used to thinking of credit as good, for example the website might say (to paraphrase Charles Horngren, an accounting great from a few years ago) “You deserve credit for your good work on the KhanAc accounting quiz today!”.  However, for accounting credit (right side) is neither good nor bad, and must always be accompanied by an equal debit (left side) anyway.  This is because the company cannot get resources (debit) without exchanging something for them (credit).  The only time a transaction is “good” is when it results in an income or gain for the company.  In this case net assets increase (debit) and there is a need for a balancing credit.  As we discussed above, this is to the stockholder (and is a credit to retained earnings)."
