# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Examples of this data are:   "
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "If there is one single decision that is paramount for the users of financial statements (which, as we mentioned, is the principal product of the financial accounting system), it is the decision of the stockholder or potential stockholder as to whether to purchase common equity stock, hold existing stock, or sell/sell short stock in the company."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In dealing with the first problem, the accounting system aggregates data to produce reports which are useful to the decision maker.  For example, if a manager within the company is trying to decide whether to order more cornflakes for stores in California, he or she will want a report on what the recent sales of cornflakes are in that state."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In dealing with the second problem, the accounting system draws a distinction between users internal to the company and users external to the company.  Internal users of the company’s data (i.e. company managers) are allowed relatively unrestricted access to the company’s data via the company’s management accounting system.  External users of company’s data will be able to access a subset of the company’s data which is produced by the company’s financial accounting system.  That subset of data is called the company’s financial statements (including the notes to the financial statements)."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "In this decision, the stockholder is most interested in the financial performance of the company which is reporting its information.  In accounting this financial performance is measured by the net income generated by the company.  Net income is calculated as sales revenue received from customers minus expenses (costs of doing business).  The calculation of net income is something that we will discuss extensively in the following modules, but we would note here that net income is not the same as net cash received.  This is because the accounting system makes improvements to the measurement of income relative to cash flow.  One example of this is allowing revenues to be “counted” even if the cash has not yet been received, as long as the customer is creditworthy.  The calculation of net income is carried out in the income statement of the company."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Society has an interest in company financial information being clearly and honestly disclosed.  The availability of unbiased and decision-relevant information about companies helps stockholders decide which companies to invest in and encourage, and which companies to deprioritize (sell).  This in turn leads to efficient and effective allocation of Society’s resources out of unattractive businesses and into attractive businesses – thus helping economic growth in the long run.  Extensive time and effort is put into defining accounting principles and rules that lead to fair and useful information being published by companies (accounting standard setting, principally carried out by the Financial Accounting Standards Board (FASB)) and also into ensuring that individual companies abide by those rules (including the auditing process, carried out by independent Certified Public Accountants (CPAs) and regulated (for public companies) by the Public Company Accounting Oversight Board (PCAOB)).  This helps to ensure that investors have the information they need and that managers within companies do not overstate their company’s financial health or fraudulently use the company’s resources for their own benefit."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "Such a large mass of data has usefulness, but it is most useful when aggregated and sorted into information relevant to decisions that need to be made both inside and outside of the company.  It is this aggregation and sorting process that is the role of accounting, a comprehensive system for providing decision-useful information from the activities of the business."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "The stockholder is also interested in other information, such as the assets being used by the company and how they have been financed.  This information is contained in the balance sheet of the company."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "There are other external users of the financial accounting data as well.  Companies are treated as separate legal persons (from their owners) for the purposes of entering into contracts and taking on loans (borrowing).  Persons or banks considering lending money to a company will be interested in their financial performance as, if the performance is good, this will give some assurance that the company will be able to repay its loans.  Lenders/banks will also be interested to look at the company’s balance sheet to see how much cash and other relatively liquid assets it has (an asset is more liquid the more easily it can be sold or otherwise converted into cash).  Other users of financial information include government agencies such as regulators and tax authorities, employees and unions, and customers and other local and national stakeholders."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "There are two issues that may concern us in processing the large amount of data that a significant business produces.  The first is that the sheer amount of data may limit its usefulness to a decision maker, because he or she will not be able to absorb it all and sort out the data that is relevant to his or her activities and decisions – i.e. “data overload.”  Secondly, when thinking about how much data to make available to people external to the company (especially competitors), concerns of commercial confidentiality may arise if data is made public on matters such as cost structures and contracts with customers and suppliers."
msgstr ""

# Article is at <a href="http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview">http://translate.khanacademy.org/partner-content/berkeley-digital/intro-financial-accounting/need-for-financial-information/a/financial-information-an-overview</a>.
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: es)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: lol)
# (KA_SOURCE_TREE: shared)
# (format: perseus_text)
#: intl/datastore:1
msgid "This module of Haas at Khan Academy concentrates on the financial accounting aspect of the company’s accounting system.    For financial accounting, there is a need to strike a balance between providing too much information and too little.  Providing too much information to the external user would make the information difficult to assimilate and use, as well as exposing sensitive information to competitors to the detriment of the firm.  However, providing too little information could also be damaging.  This is because external decision makers also make decisions based on the accounting data, and they need sufficient data to make those decisions."
msgstr ""

